\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 1: (5+5+5 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall from class that if we have an 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-periodic problem with period 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

its symmetry group consists of translations 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}f(x)=f(x-na)$
\end_inset

 for all integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, then the eigenfunctions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}$
\end_inset

 are Bloch-periodic functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k}(x)e^{ikx}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k}$
\end_inset

 is periodic, corresponding to eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{(k)}(n)=e^{-ikna}$
\end_inset

 for arbitrary real 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 (but 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{(k)}=D^{(k+\frac{2\pi}{a})}$
\end_inset

).
 Equivalently, these are the partner functions of the 1d irreps 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{(k)}$
\end_inset

 (which are, in fact, the only possible unitary irreps).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that space is looped around in a torus/circle with period 
\begin_inset Formula $Na$
\end_inset

, so that translation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to translation 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{0}$
\end_inset

 (= identity).
 In this case, what are the irreps?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Solution:
\series default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{N}=\hat{0}$
\end_inset

, then we must have the same property of the irreps: 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{(k)}(N)=e^{-ikNa}=D^{(k)}(0)=1$
\end_inset

, which implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $kNa=2\pi m$
\end_inset

 for some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 That is 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\frac{2\pi m}{Na}$
\end_inset

.
 However, not all integers 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 lead to distinct irreps, because we also know that 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k+\frac{2\pi}{a}=\frac{2\pi}{Na}(m+N)$
\end_inset

 are equivalent, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m+N$
\end_inset

 are equivalent.
 Hence, the distinct irreps correspon to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{k_{m}=\frac{2\pi m}{Na}\text{ for }m=0,\ldots,N-1}
\]

\end_inset

(or equivalent, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1\ldots N$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $m=-\left\lfloor N/2\right\rfloor \ldots\left\lceil N/2\right\rceil -1$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For this finite 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-period torus, what are the projection operators for your irreps, applied
 to some arbitrary function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

? The projection operator involves a sum, and (as you saw in pset
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

4) the sum of the projection operators over all irreps is the identity —
 show that in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 (infinite periodic systems), at least one of these two sums becomes an
 integral (you may need to rearrange a normalization factor).
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Solution:
\series default
 The dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 of these representations is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, and the size of the group is 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, so applying our general formula for projection operators, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{f_{k_{m}}(x)=\hat{P}^{(m)}f=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=0}^{N-1}D^{(k_{m})}(n)^{*}\hat{n}f=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{n=0}^{N-1}e^{+i\frac{2\pi}{N}mn}f(x-na),}
\]

\end_inset

which is in the form of a discrete Fourier transform (DFT) for each 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\sum_{m=0}^{N-1}f_{k_{m}}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k_{m}}(a)$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 periodic, it is Bloch-periodic: by construction, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{k_{m}}(x-a)=e^{-i\frac{2\pi}{N}m}f_{k_{m}}(x)$
\end_inset

 via the change of variables 
\begin_inset Formula $n'=n+1$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

To take the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 limit, we will want to shift the 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

 normalization factor to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{m}$
\end_inset

, so we will define 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{k_{m}}(x)=Nf(x)$
\end_inset

.
 It is also useful to rewrite the sums starting at zero to something like
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n=0}^{N-1}=\sum_{n=-\left\lfloor N/2\right\rfloor }^{\left\lceil N/2\right\rceil -1}
\]

\end_inset

 so that we remove anything special about the origin 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leftrightarrow N$
\end_inset

 from the sum (since it is weird to have 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wrap to infinity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 limit).
 Then, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{k_{m}}(x)=Nf_{k_{m}}(x)\longrightarrow\boxed{F_{k}(x)=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}e^{+ikna}f(x-na)\text{ for }k\in[0,\frac{2\pi}{a})}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{m=0}^{N-1}F_{k_{m}}(x)=\frac{a}{2\pi}\sum_{m}F_{k_{m}}(x)\underbrace{\frac{2\pi}{Na}}_{\Delta k}\longrightarrow\boxed{f(x)=\frac{a}{2\pi}\int_{0}^{2\pi/a}F_{k}(x)dk}\:,
\]

\end_inset

corresponding exactly to a 
\series bold
Fourier series 
\series default
(or DTFT) and its inverse.
 The latter may not 
\emph on
look
\emph default
 like the inverse of a Fourier series, but remember that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{k}(x)$
\end_inset

 is Bloch-periodic — if we change variables to a periodic coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{k}(x)=e^{-ikx}F_{k}(x)=u(x+a)$
\end_inset

, then we get something that looks more conventional: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{k}(x)=\sum_{n}e^{-ik(x-na)}f(x-na)\Longleftrightarrow f(x)=\frac{a}{2\pi}\int_{0}^{2\pi/a}e^{+ikx}u_{k}(x)dk\:.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose that we have Maxwell's equations in an 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-periodic system 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(x,y,z)=\varepsilon(x+a,y,z)$
\end_inset

.
 You saw in pset
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

1 that the response to a time-harmonic current source is given by the solution
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nabla\times\nabla\times{}-\omega^{2}\varepsilon)\vec{E}=i\omega\vec{J}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}=\mu_{0}=c=1$
\end_inset

 units); here, the operator on the left commutes with 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Now, however, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
periodic or Bloch-periodic, and just is some arbitrary current distribution
 (e.g.
 maybe it is localized in a finite region of space).
 Explain how we could still solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 by solving a 
\emph on
set
\emph default
 of problems with Bloch-periodic boundaries and summing or integrating the
 results.
 (Hint: apply your projection operator.) (This is a very practical computational
 tool for modeling periodic systems with non-periodic sources!)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Solution:
\series default
 From above, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}(x,y,z)=\frac{a}{2\pi}\int_{0}^{2\pi/a}\vec{J}_{k}(x,y,z)dk$
\end_inset

 can be written as a superposition of Bloch-periodic sources by a projection
 operation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{J}_{k}(x,y,z)=\sum_{n=-\infty}^{\infty}e^{+ikna}\vec{J}(x-na,y,z)=e^{ika}\vec{J}_{k}(x-a,y,z)\:.
\]

\end_inset

So, we can solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 by:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Approximate the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}(x,y,z)=\frac{a}{2\pi}\int_{0}^{2\pi/a}\vec{J}_{k}(x,y,z)dk$
\end_inset

 by a sum (a ``quadrature rule'') over a finite set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{k_{m}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 values.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\emph on
Comment: 
\emph default
Since the integrand is periodic in 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, a good choice is simply equally spaced points 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{m}=\frac{2\pi m}{Na}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m=0,\ldots,N$
\end_inset

 for a sufficiently large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 as we did in the previous part, i.e.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}(x,y,z)\approx\frac{1}{N}\sum_{m=0}^{N-1}\vec{J}_{k_{m}}(x,y,z)$
\end_inset

, exactly the reverse of the limit of the previous section (corresponding
 to approximating the infinite periodic system by a ``supercell'' of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 unit cells).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For each ``quadrature point'' 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{m}$
\end_inset

, compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}_{k_{m}}$
\end_inset

 by the projection operation above, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the unit cell 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,a)$
\end_inset

.
 If the current is localized in a finite region as suggested, then the sum
 can be truncated to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

's for which 
\begin_inset Formula $x-na$
\end_inset

 lies within the support of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}$
\end_inset

.
 (More generally, assume that the sum is converging so that we can compute
 it easily to any desired accuracy.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For each Bloch-periodic current 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}_{k_{m}}$
\end_inset

, solve Maxwell's equations in the unit cell 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,a)$
\end_inset

 with Bloch-periodic boundary conditions for the corresponding electric
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}_{k_{m}}(x,y,z)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}(x,y,z)=\frac{a}{2\pi}\int_{0}^{2\pi/a}\vec{E}_{k}(x,y,z)dk$
\end_inset

 (for any desired 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

), where again the 
\begin_inset Formula $\int dk$
\end_inset

 is approximated by our sum over 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{m}$
\end_inset

 (our quadrature rule).
 This is the desired solution! 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
