\begin_layout Standard
Refer to the solutions for problem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3 of pset
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

2 (recently updated to fix a couple of typos), in which we put a time-harmonic
 current source 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}=f(x)\delta(y)e^{-i\omega t}\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 into a PEC waveguide (waves traveling along the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 direction) and found the (
\begin_inset Formula $H_{z}$
\end_inset

-polarized) solutions as an infinite cosine series of propagating + evanescent
 modes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that the cosine-series coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)/2$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 even and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}=\frac{1}{n^{2}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 odd (corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $x-L/2$
\end_inset

, but you need not go through the integrals).
 Compute the rate of power 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\omega)$
\end_inset

 expended by the current source (e.g.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

with the help of Poynting's theorem), and sketch a plot of 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\omega)$
\end_inset

 a function of frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\ge0$
\end_inset

 (capturing the main qualitative features).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall from pset
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

2 that the solution for the magnetic field looked like: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{z}(x,y)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_{n}\cos\left(\frac{n\pi x}{L}\right)e^{ik_{n}|y|-i\omega t}\operatorname{sign}(y),
\]

\end_inset

for propagating/evanescent modes 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}=+\sqrt{\omega^{2}-\left(\frac{n\pi}{L}\right)^{2}}$
\end_inset

 (for 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1$
\end_inset

 units and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>0$
\end_inset

) with Fourier cosine-series coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}=\frac{1}{L}\int_{0}^{L}f(x)\cos\left(\frac{n\pi x}{L}\right)dx\:.
\]

\end_inset

By Poynting's theorem, we can compute the (time-average) power 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\omega)$
\end_inset

 expended by the current source either by computing the Poynting flux or
 by computing the (time-average) work
\series bold
 expended
\series default
 by the current source on the field (note the sign): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\omega)=-\frac{1}{2}\Re\left[\int\vec{J}^{*}\cdot\vec{E}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Here, I will use the latter approach.
 Either way, we first need to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{x}$
\end_inset

, which is given from Ampere's law 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\times\vec{H}=-i\omega\varepsilon\vec{E}+\vec{J}$
\end_inset

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $y\ne0$
\end_inset

, where we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=1$
\end_inset

, this gives 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{x}=-\frac{1}{i\omega}\frac{\partial H_{z}}{\partial y}=-\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_{n}\frac{k_{n}}{\omega}\cos\left(\frac{n\pi x}{L}\right)e^{ik_{n}|y|-i\omega t}\:,
\]

\end_inset

(where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 factors helpfully cancel out).
 Notice that the limits 
\begin_inset Formula $y\to0^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 agree — 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{x}$
\end_inset

 is continuous and well defined at 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

.
 (Recall from pset
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

2 that the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{z}$
\end_inset

 across its jump at 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

 gives the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 function in 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{J}$
\end_inset

, so Ampere's law is now satisfied everywhere.) The power is now: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\omega)=-\frac{1}{2}\Re\left[\int\vec{J}^{*}\cdot\vec{E}\right]=\frac{1}{2}\Re\left[\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_{n}\frac{k_{n}}{\omega}\underbrace{\int_{0}^{L}f(x)^{*}\cos\left(\frac{n\pi x}{L}\right)dx}_{La_{n}^{*}}\right]=\boxed{\frac{L}{2\omega}\Re\left[\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}|a_{n}|^{2}k_{n}\right]}\,,
\]

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(y)$
\end_inset

 eliminated the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 integral, the 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 integral gave us an 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}^{*}$
\end_inset

 term, and some other nice simplifications happened.
 In fact, a further simplication occurs because 
\series bold
most of the terms in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n}$
\end_inset

 are zero
\series default
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}$
\end_inset

 is imaginary (evanescent) for all but a finite number of terms 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{n<\frac{L\omega}{\pi}}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we can simplify this further to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\omega)=\frac{L}{2}\sum_{0\le n<\frac{L\omega}{\pi}}|a_{n}|^{2}\sqrt{1-\left(\frac{n}{\omega L/\pi}\right)^{2}}\ge0.
\]

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $L\omega/\pi<1$
\end_inset

, so that this only has the 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 term, we have a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $P=|a_{0}|^{2}L/2$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $L\omega/\pi$
\end_inset

 passes through each positive integer (corresponding to the cutoff of each
 successive propagating mode), we get a square-root singularity (infinite
 slope).
 Note that this power is always nonnegative as expected! An example of what
 this could look like is shown in Fig.
