\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Comment on solutions: van Hove Singularities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The singularities in the power 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\omega$
\end_inset

) that occur when new propagating modes appear (i.e.
 at band edges) is called a 
\emph on
van Hove singularity
\emph default
, and is well known in solid-state physics.
 However, if you are already familiary with van Hove singularities, you
 may have noticed something that seems mysterious at first glance: the square
 root singularity that we see above is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wrong singularity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for 1d.
 In a 1d band structure (only one direction of translational symmetry =
 one direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

), the singularity in the power (or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

local density of states
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) is genericaly an 
\emph on
inverse square root
\emph default
 singularity, corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re[k_{n}^{-1}]$
\end_inset

.
 The ``mere'' square-root singularity 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re[k_{n}]$
\end_inset

 that we get here is much weaker, and is generically what one expects from
 van Hove singularities in 
\emph on
3d
\emph default
.
 (These dependencies can be derived from density-of-states ``counting''
 arguments where you integrate 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n}\int\delta(\omega-\omega_{n}(\vec{k}))\,dk$
\end_inset

 around a band edge 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{n}\sim\Vert\vec{k}\Vert^{2}+\cdots$
\end_inset

 in various dimensions, and are discussed in many solid-state physics textbooks.)
 What is going on here that is special?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fact, you do see the ``expected'' 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re[k_{n}^{-1}]$
\end_inset

 singularity for a 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{z}$
\end_inset

 current source exciting 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{z}$
\end_inset

-polarized modes, so the behavior here is unique to the 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{z}$
\end_inset

 polarization.
 What's going on here originates from the fact that the 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{z}$
\end_inset

-polarized solution at cutoff 
\begin_inset Formula $(k=0$
\end_inset

) is a standing wave of planewaves propagating in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm x$
\end_inset

 direction (orthogonal to the direction of translational symmetry), which
 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{z}$
\end_inset

 polarization have an electric field 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 that lies entirely in the 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 direction.
 But with this polarization, 
