\begin_layout Standard
In class, we have mostly considered the simplified case where the electric
 polarization density 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{P}$
\end_inset

 responds 
\emph on
instantaneously
\emph default
 and linearly to the electric field at the same point in space: 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{P}(\vec{x})=\chi_{\text{e}}\vec{E}(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 for some constant ``susceptibility'' 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\text{e}}=\varepsilon-1$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, however, changing 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{P}$
\end_inset

 involves physically moving electric charges, and so it cannot happen instantane
ously.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imagine a simple model in which the charges are attached to immobile atoms
 with linear springs, so that they can bounce back and forth with some frequency
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 in the absence of external forces.
 (This actually turns out to be a reasonable semiclassical model of an atom
 with an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

electric dipole transition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 energy difference 
\begin_inset Formula $\hslash\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 between a ground state and an excited state.) Of course, there also needs
 to be some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

friction
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 so that the atom slowly settles down (to its ground state) when it is left
 alone.
 A simple model for this is to describe 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{P}$
\end_inset

 by a damped harmonic oscillator at each point in space: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{\vec{P}}=-\omega_{0}^{2}\vec{P}-\gamma_{0}\dot{\vec{\vec{P}}}+\sigma_{0}\vec{E}
\]

\end_inset

for a frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

, a damping rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0}>0$
\end_inset

 , and a coupling coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}>0$
\end_inset

 to the electric field at that point in space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Assuming time-harmonic fields 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{P}$
\end_inset

 proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset

, show that you obtain the same Maxwell equations as in class but with a
 
\emph on
frequency-dependent
\emph default
 permittivity 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon(\omega,\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 (where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 dependence arises if your coefficients above vary with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Solution: 
\series default
For time-harmonic solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}(\vec{x})e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{P}(\vec{x})e^{-i\omega t}$
\end_inset

, the equation becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $-\omega^{2}\vec{P}=-\omega_{0}^{2}\vec{P}+i\omega\gamma_{0}\vec{P}+\sigma_{0}\vec{E}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{P}=\underbrace{\frac{\sigma_{0}}{(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2})-i\omega\gamma_{0}}}_{\chi_{e}(\omega,\vec{x})}\vec{E},
\]

\end_inset

where we have identified the proportionality factor as 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{e}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 (the electric susceptibility) from class.
 Hence (from class), 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\varepsilon(\omega,\vec{x})=1+\chi_{e}(\omega,\vec{x})=1+\frac{\sigma_{0}}{(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2})-i\omega\gamma_{0}}}.
\]

\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 dependence (if any) comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}(\vec{x}),\gamma_{0}(\vec{x}),\sigma_{0}(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if we have a single kind of polarizable material in some regions
 of space and vacuum (
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=1$
\end_inset

) in other regions, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{0}$
\end_inset

 will be constants while 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}$
\end_inset

 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in vacuum and some positive constant in the material.
\end_layout

